helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: A list of all R-Apps installed on your router. Non-critical R-Apps can be disabled from running when the router is switched on.
addedPcMessage@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netd: You have added a PC game to the Geo-Filter. As most PC games do not require a Geo-Filter, we have automatically set the toggle to 'Spectator Mode'. The Geo-Filter will show you the server you have connected to which you can then ping, but it will not be blocked. If you would like servers to be filtered, click the toggle to change it to 'Filtering Mode'.
helpContentCaption1@/dumaos/apps/usr/com: Anti-Bufferbloat is disabled when the sliders are set to 100%. If something is using all your bandwidth then small applications like games will be forced to queue, causing lag.
qosFeaturesDisabledContent@/dumaos/apps/: This has stopped QoS from eliminating network congestion and it has also affected other features on this router, including Deep Packet Inspection. To re-enable QoS, open the Options menu on the Anti-Bufferbloat panel and uncheck the Disable all QoS option.
helpContentCaption2@/dumaos/apps/usr/com: Lower the sliders below 100% to limit the total bandwidth the greedy devices can take. This makes room for your smaller applications, eliminating the queuing problem.
step5Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: Save your favourite R-Apps to your personalised Dashboard, a single page where you can configure your settings with ease.
step6Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: The Application Breakdown will open in a new panel showing how much bandwidth each application is using e.g. YouTube, Facebook etc.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: The Network Snapshot is a real-time visualisation of all the devices on your network currently consuming bandwidth. Left click on a device's download or upload bar to see which applications are using the Internet.
step6Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Play a compatible, online multiplayer game on your selected device. Blocked connections outside of your radius will appear as warning triangles or padlocks and will be prevented from hosting your game. The host of your game will be inside your radius and will appear as the largest, most consistently shown icon.
step8Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Click and drag the percentage circle next to a device to change the device's download bandwidth allocation. By default, any unneeded bandwidth is automatically given to any other devices that do need it.
deviceBlockedWarning@/dumaos/apps/system: You have now blocked this device from connecting to the Internet. Select UNBLOCK if you wish to undo this. All blocked devices will appear as black icons on your Device Tree.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: The Application Breakdown shows the applications which are currently consuming bandwidth within the selected Device and Category.

helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: View the amount of RAM currently available on your router. There will be less free RAM when there are more processes running on your router.
neverChangedAlertContent@/dumaos/apps/us: You will now receive your full bandwidth speeds but your games will be caught in a queue, causing lag, when all your bandwidth is being used. To reactivate Anti-Bufferbloat, change the mode to Always or High Priority Traffic Detected and lower the sliders below 100%.
overlappingFiltersError@/dumaos/apps/usr: Unable to install because some filters are overlapping.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma:
Ping shows the connection quality (the ping) from you to the connection you have selected on the map. It is measured in milliseconds (ms).

If Auto-Ping is enabled in your Geo-Filter Map then the ping shown is the ping from you to the host / server of your game.
step4Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: To go to a different DumaOS R-App, click on its icon in the left-hand navigation menu.
step8Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: That completes the setup for the Network Monitor R-App. If you need further help, click on each panel's Help Icon for more information.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma: The Geo-Filter reduces the main cause of lag by limiting the distance of the hosts or servers you play on. Set your home using <iron-icon icon='maps:person-pin-circle'></iron-icon> and then set a distance range. Any player or server outside of this range will be prevented from hosting your game. Use the magnifying glass icon <iron-icon icon='zoom-in'></iron-icon> to zoom in on an area of the map. Load recommended Geo-Filter settings for you favorite game by clicking the PROFILES button.
Bandwidth Allocation allows you to give a percentage of your total bandwidth to each of the devices on your network. This guarantees bandwidth for a device whenever it needs it.
step1Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: The Device Manager shows you the devices that are connected to your router and allows you to block any unwanted devices.
helpContentSpectatingMode@/dumaos/apps/u: Spectating mode will not block connections outside of your radius. This is recommended for most PC games which do not require filtering.
step2Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: The NETGEAR Portal has an additional navigation menu on the left-hand side where you can move between different Nighthawk settings.
step4Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Click your approximate physical location on the Geo-Filter map.
goodputEnabledInformation@/dumaos/apps/u: Each packet has a header usually about 40 - 60 bytes out of 1500 bytes. Bandwidth allocation includes the header by default so for a test like speedtest which doesn't measure headers it will seem like your speed is lower than it is. Goodput means assign extra bandwidth to accommodate the headers so your bandwidth is closer to the speedtest result.
step2Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: The Device Tree shows your network setup, with separate branches for devices connected via wired LAN, via WiFi and the devices which are currently offline. Click on a device to view its information.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: Essential system information about your router
helpTip@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netdumas: Left click on a device to access its settings.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: Essential settings for your router, including WiFi. Select the tab at the top of the panel that you wish to configure.
helpContentTip@/dumaos/apps/system/com.n: Only disable a R-App from running on startup if you are experiencing issues and have been advised to by technical support.
step7Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: Use the Geo-Filter to reduce lag in your favourite games by guaranteeing a host close to your home. You can also view your ping to the game's host / server and see the location of other players in your game.
step4Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: You can change the device's type e.g. console, PC etc, by selecting a new device type from the drop-down menu. Click Update to save your changes.
step1Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: The Dashboard is a single screen which contains the panels you have pinned from other R-Apps. This allows you to configure your favourite settings with ease.
bandwidthWarning@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.ne: Set speeds do not match latest Speedtest. Click here for more information.
unableToInstallLanesError@/dumaos/apps/u: Unable to install because lanes overlap.

step4Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: To enable Anti-Bufferbloat, set it to Always or High Priority Traffic Detected. This allows you to play games without any device or application causing you to lag. Always mode applies Anti-Bufferbloat all the time, High Priority mode applies it only when your router detects you are gaming.
languageChangeErrorMessage@/www/desktop/:
Your router's display language could not be changed. Please ensure you have are online with a working Internet connection and retry.

If the problem continues, please contact NETGEAR technical support.
drawerHelpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.n:
Download / Upload Bandwidth: enter the total bandwidth speeds you receive from your Internet Provider. If you are unsure on the values, run a Speedtest.

When the Goodput option is checked, the bandwidth values for both upload and download will more closely align to a Speedtest. We recommend you keep this option checked.

Disable all QoS will stop every QoS feature. We highly recommend you do not do this as it will prevent QoS from eliminating network congestion and it will also affect other features on this router, including Deep Packet Inspection. Only select this option if you are absolutely know what you are doing.
deletingOnlineDeviceError@/dumaos/apps/s: Unable to delete device because it is online.
helpContentIntroduction@/dumaos/apps/usr: Add the gaming device(s) you would like to use the Geo-Filter on, such as an Xbox One or PS4. Up to four devices can be selected.
step3Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: Most R-App panels have options. To access a panel's option menu, click the Options icon in the top left hand corner of the panel.
Your sliders are still set to 100%. This means that your games could still be caught in a queue, causing lag. Lower your sliders below 100% to limit the total bandwidth. This makes room for your smaller applications, eliminating the queuing problem.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: The Network Overview shows total bandwidth consumption across your network relative to your overall bandwidth speeds.
helpContentCaption2@/dumaos/apps/usr/com: With Traffic Prioritization, your most important traffic is always sent to the front of the queue. This prevents lag from occurring.
step5Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Reduce both distance sliders to a value below 100% to limit the total bandwidth the greedy devices can use. We recommend 70% for users new to DumaOS. This will now prevent congestion and lag.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: The Network Map shows your network setup, with a separate branch for devices connected via wired LAN, via WiFi and your devices which are currently offline.
step2Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Click the Options menu icon in the Anti-Bufferbloat panel to view the advanced options.
routerAboutToUpdate@/www/desktop/index.h: Your router is about to update. Please do not switch it off. It will reconnect shortly.
step3Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: View the total bandwidth speeds your router believes you receive from your Internet Provider. Change the values if you believe you receive different speeds. If you unsure on the values, run a Speedtest at speetest.net. Close the options menu when complete.
filteringSuccessMessage2@/dumaos/apps/us: If you want to play with friends who live outside of your radius you will need to add them to your Allow list by inviting to them to your game and then clicking on their connection on your Geo-Filter Map. In the Ping panel that then opens below on the right hand side, choose ALLOW.
step5Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: That completes the guide for the Dashboard R-App.
step6Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: To save any panel to your Dashboard, click on the Pin icon found in the top right corner of the panel. You can unpin the panel at any time by clicking on the Pin icon once again.
shareExcessEnabledInformation@/dumaos/ap: Re-enabling 'Share Excess' will automatically give any unused bandwidth to a device that needs it. This means devices may achieve higher speeds than the values allocated to them. For most users, we recommend 'Share Excess' is enabled.

step15Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdu: By default, Traffic Prioritisation is designed to automatically place all major gaming traffic (e.g. PSN, Xbox Live, PC games) to the front of the queue.
If the Share Excess option is checked (recommended), any unused bandwidth is automatically given to any other device that needs it. Unchecking Share Excess prevents this redistribution (not recommended for most networks).
step2Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: To save any panel to your Dashboard, click on the Pin icon found in the top right corner of the panel. You can unpin the panel at any time by clicking on the Pin icon once again.
hptNot100AlertContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/c:
You can now play games without any greedy device or application causing you to lag. Because you have set it to High Priority Traffic Detected mode, Anti-Bufferbloat will only apply when games are being played (all console games and most PC games are automatically detected by DumaOS). Your total bandwidth speeds will only be reduced when games are detected.

If you would prefer Anti-Bufferbloat to always be active, change the mode to Always.

manualSelectionServiceWarning@/www/custo: Be advised that manually selecting a service is recommended for advanced users only
lowAllocationWarning@/dumaos/apps/usr/co: You have set the slider to a value less than 10% of your total bandwidth. This will significantly reduce the bandwidth available on your network. We recommend you increase the slider to a higher value.
step6Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: Click Delete to remove an offline device from your Device Tree. The device will only reappear on your Device Tree if they connect to your network again in the future.
step3Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: If you wish to rename a device, type a new name into the Name text box. Click Update to save your changes.
drawerHelpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/co: Retry Attempts on Startup sets the amount of times the router will reattempt to start a R-App that did not successfully boot on startup. Do not change this value unless you have been instructed to by technical support.

helpTip@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netdumas: Click on a section of the pie chart to view this category's usage by application.

helpTip@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdumasoft: A ping of less than 100ms is considered to be good for gaming.
helpTip@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netdumas: Use the QoS feature set to resolve any issues caused by a device that is using too much of your bandwidth.
routerRebootingConfirmation@/dumaos/apps: Your router is now rebooting. This should take 1-2 minutes.
step1Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: The Network Monitor shows you which devices and applications are consuming your bandwidth in real-time. You can then use this information to apply the best QoS settings.

manualPortRangeAddedWarning@/dumaos/apps: You have manually selected a port / port range to be automatically prioritized. It will now be automatically prioritized by your router. You may experience congestion problems if the port(s) are being used for high bandwidth intensity applications.
helpTip@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdumasoft: Set Auto Traffic Prioritization to enabled in the side menu. This will allow the router to automatically boost gaming traffic for consoles and most major PC games. You can still manually add your own devices and services if you want.
step9Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: That completes the setup for the Geo-Filter R-App. If you need further help, click on each panel's Help Icon for more information.
step5Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Set the radius to a size you want by dragging the Distance slider. We recommend 1000km - 2000km. The radius prevents all connections outside its range from hosting your game.
drawerHelpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.n: Share Excess automatically allocates any unused bandwidth to a device that needs it. Unchecking Share Excess caps the percentage allocated to each device, preventing unneeded bandwidth from being shared across your network. We recommend you keep this option checked.
step17Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdu: If you wish to manually add a service or game to Traffic Prioritisation, click Add Device to bring up the device selector and then Select a Service to match the device type you have chosen.
step2Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: For details about what each panel is showing, click on the panel's Help Icon
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma: Set an exact bandwidth allocation for the selected device.
helpContentFilteringMode@/dumaos/apps/us: Filtering mode will block connections outside of your distance radius to force a host / server inside your radius. This is recommended for console games.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: Configure the selected device's settings, such as renaming the device, and block any unwanted devices from your network. Deleting offline devices removes the device from your Map.
helpContentCaption1@/dumaos/apps/usr/com: Normally each application using your Internet will be queued on a first-in, first-out basis.
step11Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: View information about your router, such as CPU usage and a list of your installed R-Apps.
disableAllQosWarningContent@/dumaos/apps: We highly recommend you do not disable all QoS features. Only proceed if you absolutely know what you are doing. Are you sure you wish to proceed?
cantApplySettingsError@/dumaos/apps/usr/: Unable to apply settings because the hardware is busy. Please wait a few seconds and try again. If the problem persists please restart your router.
step3Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: Click on any device's bar to open the Category Breakdown for that device.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: Log files of DumaOS's activity mainly used to assist the tech support team. Your personal data is never captured.
step1Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: The main cause of lag in console games such as Call of Duty, Destiny, FIFA and many others is the distance from you to the host or server of your game. The Geo-Filter is unique because it limits the distance of these hosts or servers. The effect on your game will be very noticeable, with improved response time and fairer gameplay.
helpTip@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdumasoft: Allocate at least 10%-20% to your gaming devices so they always have enough bandwidth.
outsideRecommendedRangeWarning@/dumaos/a: You have set your distance to a value outside of our recommended range of 500km - 3000km (311mi - 1864mi). If your range is less than 500km (311mi) you may struggle to find games. If your range is higher than 3000km (1864mi) you may not find the highest quality connections. Please adjust if you experience either of these issues.
helpContent2@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum:
If you set the Anti-Bufferbloat to Always , Anti-Bufferbloat is always applied so that you can play games without any device or application causing you to lag. However, your total bandwidth speeds are reduced. Make sure to change the setting back to Never when you are finished gaming.

High Priority Traffic Detected only applies Anti-Bufferbloat when games are played (all console games and most computer games are automatically detected by DumaOS). Your total bandwidth speeds are only reduced when games are detected.

Never disables Anti-Bufferbloat. You will receive your full bandwidth speeds but your games will be caught in a queue, causing lag, when all your bandwidth is being used.

drawerHelpTip@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdu: For beginners, we recommend you enable Auto Anti-Bufferbloat

alwaysNot100AlertContent@/dumaos/apps/us:

helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma: Traffic Prioritization information shows the number of upload and download packets that have been prioritized. A coloured circle will appear in the panel when high priority is being detected and prioritized.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: View the amount of memory available on your router. The more R-Apps you have installed on your router, the lower the amount of free space.

helpTip@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdumasoft: Before selecting ALLOW or DENY, give the connection a unique name in the Ping panel.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netduma: Allow & Deny lets you whitelist or blacklist other connections, no matter the size of your Geo-Filter. Choosing to Allow another connection will mean they can always connect to you, even if they are outside your Geo-Filter range. Choosing to Deny another connection will mean it will always be blocked, even when it is inside your Geo-Filter range. You cannot block a dedicated server. To either Allow or Deny, left click on the connection on your Geo-Filter Map. Then in the Ping panel that opens on the right hand side, choose either ALLOW or DENY.

The affected device(s) will no longer be able to access the Internet. To correct this, either re-enable 'Share Excess' in the side menu or increase all allocations to a value higher than 0%.
step1Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: DumaOS is a state-of-the-art router operating system designed to optimise your home's connection and crush lag.
always100AlertContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/c: Your sliders are still set to 100%. This means that your games could still be caught in a queue, causing lag. Lower your sliders below 100% to limit the total bandwidth. This makes room for your smaller applications, eliminating the queuing problem.
step9Content@/www/desktop/tour.html: See which devices are connected to your router and block any unwanted devices.
step4Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: You can move a pinned panel on the Dashboard by clicking and holding the R-App's name in the header at the top of the panel and then moving your mouse. Release the click button to set the new position. Your changes will be automatically saved.
step7Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: That completes the setup for the Device Manager R-App. If you need further help, click on each panel's Help Icon for more information.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: View the current utilization of your router's CPUs. The number(s) will be higher when there are more processes running on your router.
step7Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: When Auto Ping Host is enabled (toggle in the Geo-Filter Map Options), a ping graph will automatically load when you are in a game. Otherwise, you can manually click on any icon on the map to load a ping graph for that connection.
step1Content@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: System Information shows information about your router, such as CPU usage and a list of your installed R-Apps.
step1Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: When devices in your home are using all the bandwidth, it creates congestion and queuing. This causes games and other low-latency applications to lag. QoS gives you the complete toolset to solve this problem. The first tool to setup is Anti-Bufferbloat, which prevents greedy devices from maxing out your bandwidth.
upgradeConfirmationMessage@/www/desktop/: Are you sure you want to upgrade?
step12Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdu: Click Update Distribution to save your changes to Bandwidth Allocation.
step6Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: Some devices need more bandwidth than others, such as a PC on Netflix. With Bandwidth Allocation, you can control how your bandwidth is shared across all your devices.
autoHyperlaneDisableWarning@/dumaos/apps: Disabling Auto Traffic Prioritization means your router will no longer automatically apply Traffic Prioritization when it detects high priority traffic, such as games. Instead, you will need to add services and their devices to Traffic Prioritization manually. Re-enable Auto Traffic Prioritization if you would prefer the router to do this naturally.
httpsUnsupportedMessage@/www/desktop/chr: You have chosen to access DumaOS using HTTPS on Chrome which is not supported. Please switch to HTTP using the buttons below, or if you require HTTPS because you are accessing your router remotely, please use an alternative browser such as Firefox.
helpContent@/dumaos/apps/system/com.netd: Essential settings for the WAN side of your router. Only configure these settings if you are experienced with networking or have been instructed to by technical support.
qosApplicationFailedError@/dumaos/apps/u: QoS failed to apply. If the problem persists please reboot your router.
drawerHelpContent@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.n:
Kilometres / Miles toggles the units shown for distance.

Strict Mode guarantees that dedicated servers outside of your filter range will always be blocked. This should be ticked when searching in most games, except Destiny where we recommend this box is unticked.

Auto Ping Host will automatically load a ping graph which shows the quality of your connection to your game's host / server. When unchecked, you will need to manually click the host's icon on the Geo-Filter map (usually this the icon which never disappears).

Flush Cloud reloads the Geo-Filters IP list. It is only necessary to select this option if you have been advised to by technical support.
step18Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdu: That completes the setup of your QoS toolkit. If you need further help, click on each panel's Help Icon for more information.
emptyMessage@/dumaos/apps/system/com.net: This page is blank because you have not pinned any panels to your personalised Dashboard. Click the Pin icon in the top right-hand corner of your favourite panels to view them on this screen.
step8Content@/dumaos/apps/usr/com.netdum: If you wish to whitelist or blacklist a connection, click its icon on your Geo-Filter Map and then choose Allow or Deny in the Ping panel.
